                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 2.  <span>The reduction in beta cell mass is highly variable and depends on age of diagnosis.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.fig2.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.fig2.caption1.p1"></a><p>The data points, shown as black symbols, summarizes the percentage reduction in beta cell mass in 63 subjects that died within three weeks of diagnosis of type 1 diabetes mellitus from three different studies (squares <a href="#pone.0001374-Gepts1">[10]</a>, diamonds <a href="#pone.0001374-Foulis2">[9]</a>, and circles <a href="#pone.0001374-Foulis1">[8]</a>). The solid line represents the linear regression to the patients with recent onset type 1 diabetes mellitus. The 95% confidence intervals that enclose the population of recent onset type 1 diabetics patients are shown by the dashed lines.</p>
